DC  Glutathione Metabolism
DR  KEGG; map00480;
CC  Glutathione (GSH) is gamma-Glu-Cys-Gly, a thiol whose -SH group is an 
CC  important reductant in many systems. Some species use thiols other than 
CC  glutathione: mycothione in Mycobacterium tuberculosis, 
CC  gamma-glutamylcysteine in Halobacterium, and trypanothione in 
CC  trypanosomes. Cysteine and CoA may also serve. Glutathione biosynthesis
CC  is accomplished by two enzymes. First, glutamate--cysteine ligase links
CC  the gamma-COOH of Glu to the NH2 of Cys. Next, glutathione synthase
CC  creates a peptide bond from the COOH of Cys to the NH2 of Gly. Species
CC  that synthesize glutathione are likely to have a reductase for oxidized
CC  glutathione and a number of glutathione-dependent enzymes.
**  Hallmarks of a glutathione system are  obtaining it (biosynthesis from
**  Glu, Cys, Gly, ATP, or import),  using it (glutathione-dependent
**  enzymes), and  regenerating it (e.g. glutathione reductase).  TIGR01434
**  gshA 6.3.2.2 (biosynthesis) glutamate--cysteine ligase  TIGR01436 ----
**  6.3.2.2 (biosynthesis) glutamate--cysteine ligase  TIGR01380 gshB
**  6.3.2.3 (biosynthesis) glutathione synthetase  TIGR00066 ggt 2.3.2.2 
**  (cycle) gamma-glutamyltranspeptidase  TIGR01421 gor 1.6.4.2 (cycle)
**  glutathione reductase  TIGR01424 gor 1.6.4.2 (cycle) glutathione
**  reductase  TIGR00068 gloA 4.4.1.5 (uses) lactoylglutathione lyase 
**  PF00043 GST (uses) Glutathione S-transferases  Roles: biosynthesis is
**  86.  Actinomyces use a different small, cysteine-derived thiol,
**  mycothione.  Also used are gamma-glutamylcysteine in Halobacterium,
**  trypanothione  in trypanosomes. Cysteine and CoA may also serve.
